$$, $$a3511d7fa189076f0b8d8bdaab3d7c9ad160200e285489f1ca03b0b85e06b779$$, $${"A": "dfa58dc5e6da59032839c17a61ee682fda1363d383b4a55dfaac1880e2b64ae8", "C": "38a1e0f35b19b0cf7b8bfeab16b48274a6bf3af9b8a058a86b6faa691ccbd408", "D": "dabd573d1528ed1813aecd60ddcd0afe2e7707bf339234a87381c18b934b696b"}$$::jsonb, $$Budget J-Books/FY26/Defense Wide/RDTE_SOCOM_PB_2026.pdf$$, 51, $$2026-05-10T04:03:06.372628+00:00$$) ON CONFLICT DO NOTHING;
INSERT INTO public.pe_narratives (pe_id, fiscal_year, mission_description, justification, accomplishments, planned_program, performance_metrics, other_program_funding, raw_text, content_hash, section_hashes, source_pdf, source_page, ingested_at) VALUES ($$0603680S$$, 2027, $$The Defense Logistics Agency (DLA) Manufacturing Technology (ManTech) Program funds the advanced technology development needed to achieve a responsive
and efficient domestic industrial base that meets the warfighters' needs in an affordable and timely manner. The ManTech program works with DLA’s diverse supply
chains to improve manufacturing capability throughout a product's life cycle. It provides the crucial link between invention and application by maturing, scaling up, and
validating advanced manufacturing technology in “real world” environments. ManTech developments provide a path to low-risk technology implementation for many
small businesses and defense unique suppliers as well as depots and shipyards that are critical to DLA. By anticipating and addressing production and sustainment
problems before they occur, readiness levels increase, and sustainment costs are decreased.

 The ManTech R&D Program Element executes from two Lines of Effort (LOEs): Industrial Base and Aging Weapon System Support (IBA), and 3D Technical Data
 Modernization / Model-Based Enterprise (TDM). These LOEs are closely aligned to documented and tracked priorities specified in the most current DLA Strategic
 Plan, that calls for Digital Business Transformation as one of three critical capabilities to achieve DLA’s business goals of enhancing performance, reducing costs, and
 becoming more predictive and data driven.

 This critical capability also seeks to transform systems and processes to improve data transparency, reliability, and security for our employees, customers, and suppliers.
 DLA’s initiatives within this critical capability align with the National Security Strategy (NSS) by emphasizing the importance of harnessing rapid emerging technologies
 that will transform how we do business.

 - In addition to alignment with DLA’s top strategic priorities, under Section 2521 of Title 10, US Code, DLA ManTech efforts are collaborated across DoW Military
 Services and Agencies. As a Principal member of the Joint Defense Manufacturing Technology Panel, DLA’s efforts are integrated within the Joint Defense Priorities.

 -The IBA LOE seeks to implement innovative and proactive technology solutions to ensure a robust, reliable industrial base that provides affordable and previously hard-
 to-procure critical parts for DoW weapon systems. This LOE is comprised the following portfolios: DoW Subsistence Supply Chain (Subsistence Network), Castings
 (Procurement Readiness Optimization Advanced Casting Technology), Forgings (Procurement Readiness Optimization—Forging Advanced System Technology),
 Batteries (Battery Network), Additive Manufacturing (AM), Advanced Microcircuit Emulation (AME), and Strategic Materials program.
-The TDM LOE integrates three-dimensional technical data and knowledge-based tools to transform and streamline supply system responsiveness for DLA-managed
 commodities. Efforts seek to improve and facilitate the exchange of engineering and logistics information among DLA, the Military Services, DLA industry partners and
 DLA customers. The benefits include shorter product introduction cycles, lower set up costs for parts production and more economical small batch production. This LOE
 is comprised of the following portfolios for DoW soldier and individual equipment (Military Unique Sustainment Technology (MUST)) and Defense Logistics Information
 Research (DLIR), as well as out of budget cycle or Emerging Requirements (EMR).

 DLA’s focus for this budget cycle highlights advanced capabilities in digital and technical data modernization, data management and analytics to fulfill the DLA role in
 the DoW Digital Engineering Strategy and improve sharing of data with the industrial base and supported organizations. Investment explores technologies to lower the
 Agency’s material acquisition and operation costs and improve weapons systems support. This effort spans across both DLA R&D Program Elements and R&D LOEs,
 impacting across the DoW Joint Defense Manufacturing Technology Panel and DLA Enterprise logistics processes.$$, $$The three-dimensional (3D) Technical Data Modernization (TDM) / Model-Based Enterprise (MBE) includes efforts to improve and facilitate the exchange of engineering
and logistics information among DLA, the Military Services, industry partners, and customers. This LOE includes the Military Unique Sustainment Technology (MUST),
the Defense Logistics Information Research (DLIR), and the Emerging Requirements (EMR) portfolios. A primary focus of this LOE is to capitalize on the emerging
“Model Based Enterprise” paradigm and the semantic web as an enabler to a logistics system that is smart and connected and down the supply chain and across all
DLA Customers and suppliers. A major focus is to transform DoW engineering data from two-dimensional paper-based products to three-dimensional computer-based
models, and to develop processes to move from “electronic paper” (i.e. PDF files) to technical data files that can interface directly with industries’ engineering systems.
The benefits include shorter product introduction cycles, lower set up costs for parts production and more economical small batch production. Objectives for this LOE
include:

 1. Transform technical data into modern, machine-usable, neutral formats: support DoW’s digital modernization efforts and provide significant readiness improvements.
 2. Create a model-enabled knowledge base shared among DLA, the Military Services and industry: streamline the delivery of accurate requirements and high-quality
 material and end-items throughout the supply chain.
 3. Quickly develop emergent and breakthrough technologies into military significant capabilities.

 The Military Unique Sustainment Technology (MUST) program addresses GAO Report 12-707 recommendations for DoW to establish a “knowledge-based approach”
 to define, communicate, and collaborate on military unique Combat Uniforms and Individual Equipment (CUIE) requirements. DLA has the responsibility to manage
 and maintain the technical requirements among the Services and the Defense Industrial Base. Currently there is no common environment for collaborating on new
 requirements among the stakeholders. The strategic objective of the DLA MUST program is to identify, develop, and adopt technologies that can significantly improve
 the joint process from transitioning new item development to DLA sustainment and operations. The Program focuses on technologies that will transform the military
 CUIE supply chain from an “electronic paper” (i.e. PDF/MS Word) based manual environment, into a knowledge-based model driven environment. This approach will
 result in seamlessly communicating military unique technical requirements throughout the end-to-end supply chain, leading toward a Model Based Enterprise.

 The Defense Logistics Information Research (DLIR) program utilizes digital technologies to enhance the quality, security, and interoperability of logistics data,
 transforming DLA's business processes and supporting the Defense Industrial Base (DIB). A key focus of DLIR is assisting Micro, Small, and Midsize Manufacturers
 (MSMMs) in adopting Industry 4.0 practices and developing the workforce within the DIB.

                                                                                 rogram (ManTech)                         Based Enterprise

B. Accomplishments/Planned Programs ($ in Millions)                                                                                      FY 2025     FY 2026      FY 2027
Title: Three-dimensional (3D) Technical Data Modernization (TDM) / Model-Based Enterprise (MBE) (R&D LOE 2)                                 10.421       8.805        9.063
Description: FY2025 Accomplishments:

The MUST program primary focus has been to integrate the MUST developed components: 1) Supply Request Package (SRP)
Tool, 2) Interim Change Management Solution (ICMS), 3) Quality Deficiency Assessment Reporting (QDAR), and 3) the Digital
Model Library (DML) using an Application Program Interface (API), to seamlessly communicate military unique clothing and
individual equipment technical requirements throughout the supply chain. In FY2025 MUST worked closely with DLA Troop
Support Clothing and Textiles (C&T) on initiating redevelopment of the SRP Tool for SharePoint Online; continued R&D pilot
phase activities for the Interim Change Management Solution prototype; worked closely with the USMC on the requirements to
streamline input of clothing & textile defect data using handheld devices and 2D barcodes at USMC recruit training centers; and
demonstrated the functionality and broad capability of the DML, specifically on the ability to categorize specific clothing & textile
items using inferences from digital models in the library. Finally, MUST developed tools are allowing DLA Troop Support C&T to
interface with the new Military Service lead Joint Clothing Textile Modernization Initiative (JCTMI) and support the Military Services
Engineering Support Activities, and the Industrial Base.

In FY25, the DLIR program advanced DLA’s digital modernization efforts while strengthening supply chain resilience across
the Defense Industrial Base (DIB) and Organic Industrial Base (OIB). A major accomplishment was the transition of the
Celonis Process Digital Twin from a pilot capability into an enterprise tool supporting order management operations across the
agency. Analysis of more than 3.5 million orders valued at $6.61B identified approximately 18,000 process variations, revealing
opportunities to standardize workflows, reduce costs, and improve operational accuracy. The capability provides DLA with a
comprehensive “digital MRI” of enterprise processes and establishes a foundation for future robotic process automation and data-
driven process optimization.

Building on the successful transition of the Digital Sustainment Platform (DSP), DLIR shifted focus from digital engineering to
digital manufacturing to better address sustainment and industrial base requirements. Three major innovative sourcing efforts
continued to mature:

Manufacturer Database: Development of a searchable catalog of more than 80,000 manufacturers mapped to approximately
1,600 manufacturing capability categories, enabling rapid identification of potential suppliers for sustainment and surge production
requirements.

MOSAIC (Manufacturing Optimization & Supplier AI Connector): Development of AI-driven tools capable of aligning technical data
with manufacturing processes and supplier capabilities to accelerate engineering-to-production transitions.

                                                                                 rogram (ManTech)                         Based Enterprise

B. Accomplishments/Planned Programs ($ in Millions)                                                                                     FY 2025    FY 2026      FY 2027

FILOS (Flexible Industrial Logistics, Operations, and Supplier Networks): Advanced analytics and optimization tools designed to
identify U.S.-based suppliers and reduce reliance on foreign sources, improving supply chain resilience.

Additional DLIR accomplishments included workforce development support for Micro, Small, and Mid-Size Manufacturers
(MSMMs) through the MxD CAPITAL project, prototype development of Augmented and Virtual Reality (AR/VR) Remote Expert
Capabilities (REC), and completion of a DLIR program roadmap to guide future digital sustainment initiatives.

The EMR program executed Congressional add funding to support Strategic Materials and Rare Earth Element related technical
projects for: High Performance NdFeB Magnets, Hypersonic Radomes and Apertures, Nanostructured Iron Nitride Permanent
Magnets, Battery Grade Graphite, and received additional direct funding for Isomolded Graphite technology.

FY 2026 Plans:
In FY 2026, MUST plans to continue the redevelopment of the Supply Request Package Tool to SharePoint Online, continue
working with DLA Troop Support Clothing & Textiles on the adoption of the Interim Change Management Solution Tool, and
further validate the AI based tools and technical data content in the digital model library (DML), which will continue to be expanded
to make the DML information available throughout the supply chain. MUST continue to work with the Military Services to promote
the use of data formats compatible with the digital document models and identify process touch points for the Joint Clothing
& Textile Manufacturing Initiative (JCTMI). A new Broad Agency Announcement (BAA) will be issued to broaden the scope of
MUST, incorporating expanded textile manufacturing efforts and strengthening collaboration with JCTMI and AFFOA. Under the
new BAA MUST plans to include efforts utilizing containerized manufacturing at point-of-need, and improvements to the special
measurements process of unique C&T items.

In FY26, DLIR is expanding innovative sourcing capabilities while beginning integration planning to support sustainment
and acquisition lifecycle activities. Efforts to enhance the Manufacturer Database are focused on expanding the number of
manufacturers and capabilities represented in the system, incorporating additional company-level metadata, and developing more
intuitive user dashboards to improve decision support for sourcing activities.

MOSAIC enhancements will further refine AI algorithms that align engineering technical data with manufacturing capabilities,
enabling faster transitions from design data to production solutions. Work is also underway to map military standards (MIL-
STDs) to comparable commercial standards to broaden supplier participation and reduce barriers to entry for nontraditional
manufacturers.

                                                                                  rogram (ManTech)                         Based Enterprise

B. Accomplishments/Planned Programs ($ in Millions)                                                                                    FY 2025    FY 2026      FY 2027
FILOS development will continue expanding the pool of U.S.-based supplier options, improving sourcing flexibility and
strengthening resilience against foreign supply chain dependencies.

DLIR is also advancing Organic Industrial Base (OIB) modernization efforts in partnership with Air Force Materiel Command and
Army TACOM. Phase I demonstrated the ability to apply AI and machine learning to automate manufacturing data extraction,
streamline manufacturing catalogs, and improve shop capability matching. Phase II, currently undergoing government evaluation
and funding approval, proposes to expand these capabilities to additional OIB facilities while introducing automated bid
management functions and enhanced AI tools for data processing, automated bid generation, and financial system integration.

In parallel, DLIR will continue efforts to pursue an Authority to Operate (ATO) for AR/VR-based remote expert capabilities, launch
prototype development of the Reclamation, Recovery, and Resupply (R3) Lookup Tool for DLA Disposition Services, and finalize
MSMM workforce development activities under the MxD CAPITAL project.

The EMR program will continue to enable DLA's investigation of new disruptive technology advances that may be implemented in
the nearer term, without degrading well established program efforts.
FY 2027 Plans:
In FY 2027, MUST will be under a new Broad Agency Announcement (to be released in FY2026) that will broaden the scope of
MUST, incorporating efforts to validate digital technical data as the authoritative source, supply chain resilience in clothing and
individual equipment, innovation in clothing and individual equipment, and strengthening collaboration with DLA Troop Support
Clothing & Textiles, JCTMI, AFFOA, and various other DoW and industry partners.

In FY27, DLIR will transition several innovative sourcing and industrial base modernization initiatives from development
into operational capability. The innovative sourcing portfolio including the Manufacturer Database, MOSAIC, and FILOS will
reach completion and deliver integrated capabilities for identifying, analyzing, and connecting manufacturing suppliers to DLA
sustainment requirements. These tools will support more rapid identification of qualified manufacturers, accelerate engineering-
to-production transitions, and strengthen domestic supplier participation in defense sustainment activities. DLIR will also continue
Phase II of the OIB Modernization initiative, expanding AI-enabled manufacturing data extraction and shop capability mapping
across additional Organic Industrial Base facilities while advancing automated procurement capabilities.

