A. Mission Description and Budget Item Justification
Industrial Base and Aging Weapon System Support (IBA) Line of Effort seeks to implement innovative and proactive technology solutions to ensure a robust, reliable
industrial base that provides affordable and previously hard-to-procure critical parts for DoW weapon systems through the following objectives:

 1. Viable and Responsive Industrial Base: maximize Defense Industrial Base capability and capacity and improve availability, quality, and affordability to support the
 Warfighter.
 2. Obsolescence Solutions: establish a trusted manufacturing capability for qualified microcircuits to support DoW weapon system lifecycles.
 3. Advanced Manufacturing: leverage advanced manufacturing capabilities to introduce and integrate additive and advanced manufacturing concepts into the DoW
 supply chain.

 The portfolios within the IBA LOE include subsistence supply chain solutions (Subsistence Network), Castings (Procurement Readiness Optimization—Advanced
 Casting Technology), Forgings (Procurement Readiness Optimization—Forging Advanced System Technology), Batteries (Battery Network), Additive Manufacturing
 (AM), Advanced Microcircuit Emulation (AME) and Strategic Materials (SM).

 The Subsistence Network (SUBNET) program develops and promotes advanced manufacturing solutions within the subsistence supply chain for the Department of
 War (DoW) and the Defense Logistics Agency (DLA). To conduct research, development, test, and evaluation (RDT&E), SUBNET forms a community of practice with
 partners including the Military Services, U.S. Department of Agriculture, U.S. Army Combat Capabilities Development Command (DEVCOM) Soldier Center, industry,
 and academia. The program's goals are to innovate logistics processes and capitalize on the industrial base's latest technological capabilities. Desired outcomes include
 reduced costs, increased efficiency and transparency, modernized processes, enhanced quality and safety, and a greater ability to meet operational surge demands.
 SUBNET focuses on several key areas, including combat rations and field/garrison feeding solutions; food equipment, innovations, safety, and defense; nutrition and
 health; supply chain infrastructure, storage, and packaging solutions; surge and sustainment support; and water security.

 The Casting (CASTING) program works to ensure a strong, reliable, and competitive domestic casting industry capable of supporting the weapon system needs of the
 Department of War (DoW) and the DLA. It collaborates with industry, universities, and casting industry associations to identify and implement projects that improve
 materials and design resources, manufacturing processes, and business practices of the nation's foundry industry. These projects are strategically aligned with key
 issues and focus areas within the DLA and DoW, based on the DLA Strategic Plan and input from the casting industry. A significant portion of DLA's back orders, or
 unfilled orders (UFOs), are related to weapon system spare parts containing castings. Although cast parts represent only about two percent of National Stock Numbered
 Class IX parts, they contribute to approximately five percent of all backorders, and even a larger percentage, up to ten percent, of the oldest backorders. The program
 addresses this challenge by investing in tasks focused on developing and improving capabilities in areas such as manufacturing processes, workforce development, new

