 and improved materials, inspection techniques, modeling, and design tools. Once developed, these capabilities are tested and implemented within the foundry industry,
 often in partnership with casting industry associations. These advancements strengthen the metal casting supply chains for the DoW and the DLA, ultimately providing
 better support for the warfighter. The program prioritizes investments in projects that reduce lead-times and costs, while simultaneously improving the quality of castings
 crucial to DoW weapon systems.

 The Forging (FORGING) program is focused on ensuring a strong, reliable, and competitive domestic forging industry capable of supporting the weapon system needs
 of the Department of War (DoW) and the DLA. The program collaborates with industry, universities, and the Forging Industry Association to identify and implement
 projects that improve materials and design resources, manufacturing processes, and business practices of the nation's forging industry. These projects are strategically
 aligned with key issues and focus areas within the DLA and DoW, based on the DLA Strategic Plan and input from the forging industry. A large portion of DLA's
 backorders, or unfilled orders (UFOs), are related to weapon system spare parts containing forging components. Although forged parts represent only about two
 percent of National Stock Number (NSN) Class IX parts, they contribute to approximately five percent of all backorders, and even a larger percentage, up to ten
 percent, of the oldest backorders. The program addresses this challenge by investing in projects focused on developing new capabilities in areas such as inspection
 techniques, materials, manufacturing processes and optimization, workforce development, modeling, and design tools. Once developed, these capabilities are tested
 and implemented within the forging industry, often in partnership with the Forging Industry Association. These advancements strengthen the forging supply chains for
 the DoW and the DLA, ultimately providing better support for the warfighter. The program prioritizes projects that reduce lead-times and costs, while at the same time
 improving the quality of forgings crucial to DoW weapon systems.

 The Battery Network (BATTNET) program objective is to develop the next generation of battery manufacturing technologies for cost and price efficiency, longer shelf
 life, and lighter batteries with higher energy. BATTNET conducts R&D initiatives to address sustainment gaps and bridge technical solutions into higher a Manufacturing
 Readiness Level (MRL) for specific groups of batteries. BATTNET also focuses on projects to develop the production capability for advanced lithium-based non-
 rechargeable and rechargeable batteries to ensure the prompt and sustained availability, quality, and affordability of Service approved batteries. Desired outcomes
 include: streamlined inventory and associated cost reductions through standardization and improved distribution practices; resolved obsolescence issues; addressed
 surge and sustainment issues; enhanced security of supply chain; increased competition and manufacturing base; reduced per unit battery cost; and leveraged Service-
 level (Army, Navy, Air Force) and other governmental (DOE, DOT, NASA) R&D efforts to insert new technology and practices into the existing DLA battery inventory.

 The Additive Manufacturing (AM) program objective is focused on enhancing the resilience, readiness and sustainment of military systems through the integration of
 advanced 3D part manufacturing technologies as a core component of advanced manufacturing applications. By embedding AM as a core capability within defense
 manufacturing, the program aims to improve the durability, maintainability, and lifecycle support of critical assets of military systems, particularly those facing legacy and
 obsolescence challenges. The program intends to strengthen supply chain agility by operationalizing key AM dimensions – methods, materials, manpower, metrics, and
 machines, creating a cohesive, responsive and adaptable supply chain framework that effectively addresses rapid part production and system sustainment for legacy
 and obsolescence part challenges, ensuring continuous warfighter support. Through applied research, the program will accelerate AM adoption across joint operational
 environments by expanding capabilities of diverse manufacturing processes, develop analytical tools for efficient part selection, enhancing tech quality assurance,
 and qualifying vendors to meet defense standards. It also prioritizes the establishment of scalable and interoperable technical data architectures to support seamless
 data management and exchange throughout the product production lifecycle. Investigates sustainable AM feedstock inventory solutions to ensure long-term material
 availability. Drives modernization and optimization in reverse engineering capabilities within the AM ecosystem to support the reproduction of legacy components


