Description: FY2025 Accomplishments:

The SUBNET program championed RDT&E projects that enhanced the efficiency, quality, and safety of the DoW subsistence
supply chain. Through collaboration with its partners, SUBNET successfully executed projects leveraging the latest technologies.
Key accomplishments included improving subsistence visibility by validating barcode scanning and further exploring the
technology application to Operational Rations (OPRATS); investigating sustainable packaging options for Meals, Ready-to-
Eat (MREs); and supporting PFAS remediation by advancing a congressional interest project on flake graphite-based, fluorine-
free foam solutions for per- and polyfluoroalkyl substances (PFAS) contamination. SUBNET also advanced several topics with
promising results in waste management systems for separation, composting, recycling, and repurposing; a deployable kitting
platform for Unitized Group Rations (UGRs); robotic automation in dining facilities; improved heating and hydration modules for
cold-weather combat rations; and biodegradable cellulosic biopolymers as a replacement for plastics in food packaging.

The CASTING program continued research and development efforts focused on ensuring a viable and competitive metal casting
industrial base providing affordable and high- quality parts for the Warfighter. The program partners to improve the material,
manufacture, and procurement of defense parts containing castings, and to educate current and future work force on industrial
practices to better solicit and procure parts with cast content. The program executed multiple projects aimed at improving DLA’s
casting procurement agility and supply base to support warfighter readiness. The program also executed projects to reduce lead

