working directing with these suppliers to maintain and sustain and competitive forging supply chain. Specific focus was placed
on workforce development and resources to ensure a capable and educated future workforce. Coatings for dies and billets that
reduced environmental impact from sprayed lubricants, increased product quality and reduced waste and lead time. Integrated
sensors and sensor technologies to monitor and improve the forging manufacturing process.

The BATTNET program successfully designed and tested improved nickel-cadmium UPS batteries and safe lithium-ion versions
with Navy engineering activities and high-performance BB-2590 batteries with Army engineering activities. Successfully completed
tests at US Army DEVCOM of AGM lead-acid battery replacements for obsolete MIL-11188 batteries linked to the Bradley Fighting
Vehicle and other systems. The program completed manufacturing enhancements and product designs at key developers for
high energy, ground vehicle lithium-ion 6T batteries (MIL-32565) and completed a DoW funded project with manufacturing
enhancements for nickel-zinc batteries for a variety of War applications. The program also completed manufacturing trials and
enhancements for LTO and LVO cells that display excellent safety, long cycle life, and low temperature performance – vendors
secured new DoW R&D contracts for critical applications. The program completed six small business contracts for electrode and
materials production methods, mobile-safe deactivation for end-of-life lithium batteries, and lithium-ion manufacturing for Army and
Navy applications.

The Additive Manufacturing (AM) program achieved significant milestones that directly addressed critical supply chain
vulnerabilities and enhanced operational readiness. The JAMA IV project successfully addressed shortfalls by publishing
a comprehensive playbook and establishing a robust Indefinite Delivery/Indefinite Quantity (IDIQ) contract vehicle, which
strengthens the Defense Industrial Base and accelerates the integration of AM parts into military systems. Concurrently, the AM
Tooling for Testing project equipped the Product Test Center at DLA Weapons Support Columbus with 3D printing capabilities,
enabling the rapid production of bespoke fixturing and jigs. This initiative enhanced workflow, increased testing capabilities, and
developed in-house expertise in advanced thermoplastics and the mechanical testing of AM parts. Furthermore, the AM Universal/
Generic Spare Parts Initiative, in partnership with the C5ISR Center, identified opportunities to augment the DoW supply system.
This effort resulted in the successful demonstration of a "Waveguide Repair Kit" for field use and the successful 3D manufacturing
of a universal BiCone Antenna, (S-band) part, proving AM's viability for producing multi-service components.



