Description: FY2025 Accomplishments:

The Energy Readiness Program continued support of the Congressional Add funded project with the University of Maine, Woody
Biomass Conversion to Liquid Hydrocarbon Fuels. Following completed operational campaigns on producing synthetic crude oil
for commercial and military fuel upgrades, University of Maine is working for pre-commercial production validation with a major oil
refinery for hand-off of the technology in supporting developing industry goals in Maine and New England.

University of Maine is also coordinating with petroleum industry and standardization organization for commercial certification and
acceptance into production and procurement specification and standards.

ERP also managed successful completion of two President’s Budget funded projects:

Test and Evaluation of Alternative Rocket Fuels (TEARF) – Involved the selection, analysis, and experimental evaluation of
existing or readily available alternative rocket kerosene formulations on multiple scales in order to (1) Screen promising existing
fuel candidates, several of which have been successfully qualified and certified for aviation use; (2) Suggest processing and
manufacturing options resulting in optimum product composition and properties; and (3) Identify potential technology and logistic/
supply gaps hindering the use of these fuels in space launch applications.

Evaluation of Hypersonic Conditions Using CRAFTI (Compact Rapid Assessment of Fuel Thermal Integrity) - Developed an
accurate, straightforward, and repeatable specification test methodology to screen the endothermic fuels necessary for thermal
management of >MACH 5 hypersonic flight. The thermal oxidative stability of hydrocarbon jet fuels is normally screened using
an ASTM defined standard test method called Jet Fuel Thermal Oxidation Test (JFTOT) (ASTM D 3241); however, this method
has proven to be inadequate in the measurement of hypersonic fuels. CRAFTI has proven to be effective in determination of this
critical property.

