B. Accomplishments/Planned Programs ($ in Millions)                                                                                  FY 2025    FY 2026      FY 2027

The Acquisition Modernization Technology Research (AMTR) Program finalized individually tailored Market Intelligence projects
at DLA Clothing & Textile and DLA Medical, completing expansion of the current Market Intelligence program to the entire
DLA enterprise. Other efforts included a comprehensive look at improving DLA’s Contract Quality processes: designing visual
dashboard prototypes and identifying multiple AI/ML use cases to enhance contract quality control capabilities. In addition, AMTR
demonstrated an enterprise-wide smart contract proof of concept for ULO process resolution, as well as managed an AI-powered
Digital Supply Chain Twin clickable prototype solution to Clothing and Textiles that is currently in the process of transitioning.

SCMS provided the Military Services and DLA prime vendors in FY25 over 3,872 Trade Agreement Act (TAA) compliant Class 4
suppliers and over 65,023 TAA compliant products that can be sourced locally in 170 countries in USINDOPACOM, CENTCOM,
EUCOM and AFRICOM providing a cost effective procurement tool and a key capability enabler for DLA Prime Vendors,
Geographic Combatant Commands, and the Military Services supporting Force Projection, Warfighter Readiness and Resiliency.
This portable digital database has been used extensively in Military Exercises impacting $1.2B class 4 purchases annually and led
to $200M new sources of Class 4 revenues for DLA. Completed products have transitioned with Troop Support Construction and
Equipment appearing in its LogX website.

Completing the plans we set out in FY25, SCM-S conducted extensive widescale testing in 40 countries for the palette trackers
of its block-chained Next Generation Transponders (NGT) enabled by satellite, cellular and GPS in partnership with U.S.
Transportation Command (USTRANSCOM), the Military Services, and the Geographic Combatant Commands. Many high
value high visibility movements were tracked persistently providing unprecedented visibility for Commanders and Department
of War mobility teams. Focusing on the last mile, the use cases included many transcontinental moves and intra-theater
movements including warzone areas such as Ukraine and Kuwait for Operation Epic Fury. The tracking device obtained Hazards
of Electromagnetic Radiation to Ordnance (HERO) certification in 2025 allowing the Department of War to track U.S. ammunitions
loaded in Iraqi trucks. High value assets such as the Modular Protective System - Overhead Cover (MPSOHC) costing over
$1M per shipment that provides critical protection for military personnel and assets against various threats, including blasts and
ballistic impacts was tracked and closely watched by CENTCOM leadership and commanders. The In-transit Visibility from the
block-chained tracking device went directly to government systems. With over one million hours of testing with zero failures to
date, Department of War logistics contractors supporting Top Tier military exercises such as BALIKATAN started purchasing the
tracking devices. The devices detected and reported in near-real time, all actual attempted thefts and Enemy reconnaissance of
the Defense Logistics Agency (DLA) high value assets. The 21st Air Force focused on contested logistics began using the devices
to track many intra-theater movements in the USINDOPACOM area of responsibility focusing on small isolated austere islands.
NGT also provided Commanders, the actual routes taken by commercial carriers, the ability to redirect assets while in-transit, and
global hotspot areas where theft, redirections, and interdictions of Department of War assets occur regularly.


