FY 2026 Plans:
The Energy Readiness Program (ERP) will continue working with DLA Energy Service customers to improve specifications and
standards for fuel quality, engage in modeling and simulation of the energy supply chain and identifying alternative energy.

ERP will also focus on determining R&D solutions for ongoing issues affecting fuel and fuel additive quality and operational
requirements (e.g., thermal stability, storage stability, ignition capability). The program will continue to assist the military services
in the qualification and certification of alternative fuels to meet military specification requirements; adjustments to similar FY 25/26
efforts in this area will be made in accordance to changing administration and industry goals and achievements.

The Acquisition Modernization Technology Research (AMTR) program will continue to focus on improving acquisition and
procurement processes, including an AI commerciality determination and pricing capability and building further technical
requirements related to contract quality AI/ML use cases.

Based on the success of COMPASS (Compliance in Military Procurement and Supply Systems) in 2025, the 2026 focuses on
SOUTHCOM (now part of Western Hemisphere Command) to create a highly portable, simple, and flexible digital database of
construction and equipment procurement-ready data (National Stock Numbers, Trade Agreement Act compliant vendors and
products in specific countries).

Complete a new product called PIPES (Pre-procurement Information for Planning & Engineering Services) as a companion for
COMPASS providing in-depth look at the state of the country’s Class 4 supply and suggests mitigation strategies at the pre-
procurement phase, such import regulations, in cases of shortages. PIPES for key countries in USINDOPACOM, CENTCOM and
SOUTHCOM will be completed in FY26.

SCM-S will also focus on Airfield Damage Repair (ADR) in FY26 particularly for materials used for ballistic damaged airfield
with craters larger than 30 feet in diameter for Base Recovery After Attack (BRAAT). Existing Airfield Damage Repair (ADR)
approaches rely on heavy equipment, mixing infrastructure, vibration or imported aggregates. SCM-S will focus on a rapid, low
logistics airfield damage repair solution that uses minimal to no equipment, allows for imperfect execution, tolerates seawater,
brackish water, and gains rapid strength supporting aircraft operations in hours. Solution focuses on austere bases with no
electricity under wartime scenario and/or extreme climatic conditions.

