B. Accomplishments/Planned Programs ($ in Millions)                                                                                         FY 2025    FY 2026      FY 2027

As part of the ADR effort, SCM-S will also focus on heat tolerant rapid setting cement critical for contested logistics in Operation
Epic Fury and USINDOPACOM “Be Everywhere” strategy. Rapid repair of concrete pavements is an urgent operational need for
the Warfighter, spanning both conventional airfield damage repair (e.g., crater and slab repairs) and high temperature pavements
required for modern aircraft operations. In particular, the F-35B short-takeoff/vertical-landing (STOVL) capability subjects
pavement surfaces to extreme thermal loading—temperatures reported as exceeding 1,706 °F (930 °C) with very rapid heating
rates on the order of ~153 °F/s (~85 °C/s) during vertical landing events. Under these conditions, ordinary Portland cement (OPC)
concrete is vulnerable to spalling, scaling, and strength loss, creating foreign object debris (FOD) that can be ingested into aircraft
engines and degrade Mission Readiness. Spalling risk is amplified by trapped pore water and rapid heating, while spilled fuels and
oils can further reduce concrete integrity at elevated temperatures.
FY 2027 Plans:
The Energy Readiness Program (ERP) will continue to work with DLA Energy Service customers to improve specifications and
standards for fuel quality, engage in modeling and simulation of the energy supply chain and identifying alternative energy.
ERP will also focus on determining R&D solutions for ongoing issues affecting fuel and fuel additive quality and operational
requirements (e.g., thermal stability, storage stability, ignition capability). The program will continue to assist the military services
in the qualification and certification of alternative fuels to meet military specification requirements; adjustments to similar FY 25/26
efforts in this area will be made in accordance to changing administration and industry goals and achievements.

The Acquisition Modernization Technology Research (AMTR) program will continue to focus on improving acquisition and
procurement processes, exploring AI and other emerging technologies to address specific pain points and/or opportunities such
as optimizing approved DoW AI tools in acquisition subprocesses, automating past vendor evaluations, streamlining contractor
onboarding and offboarding, and predicting risks for new vendors.

Complete the transition of PIPES and COMPASS to Troop Support Construction and Equipment.

Establish an NSN for the block-chained tracking devices available for purchase for the Dept of War. Complete the Dept of
War certifications for the Heat Tolerant Rapid Setting Cement and begin testing in operationally relevant environments in
USINDOPACOM theaters.
