required to generate and better manage the enormous complexity of design, ultimately allowing designers to more easily discover
non-intuitive (yet realizable) designs that fully leverage new materials and advanced manufacturing approaches now available.
Outcomes from this thrust seek to improve the speed and accuracy of modeling and simulation, as well as enable management
of complexity across DoD devices, parts, and systems. Another focus area of this thrust is the development of quantum-assisted
approaches for predicting behavior and non-intuitive failure pathways for complex, dynamic physical systems.

Prior to FY 2026, this program was funded in PE 0601101E, Project CCS-02.

FY 2026 Plans:
- Demonstrate artificial intelligence-based predictive modeling of test problems in turbulence guided by tabletop quantum
simulators.
- Validate predictive models of test problems with computational fluid dynamical techniques.
FY 2025 to FY 2026 Increase/Decrease Statement:
The FY 2026 increase reflects the transfer of the program from PE 0601101E, Project CCS-02 to this PE/Project.
Title: Artificial Intelligence Studies and Concepts                                                                                        -             -          36.430
Description: This thrust will investigate methods to allow artificial intelligence (AI) logical inferencing to become massively
parallel and distributed. Such AI logical inferencing includes extended logic programs used for deduction (e.g., query-answering),
induction (i.e., machine learning), and abduction (e.g., argumentation and causal explanation finding). Enabling the computational
scaling up of a knowledge supply chain in AI: to harness accumulated human knowledge (notably expertise), then learn beyond
that; with high levels of abstraction, generality, and reusability will require new algorithms, and tools to create distributed
knowledge bases that efficiently yet coherently communicate and cooperate, dynamically. This was previously Emerging
Opportunities in Math and Computer Sciences.

Prior to FY 2026, this program was funded as Emerging Opportunities in Math and Computer Science in PE 0601011E, Project
CCS-02.

FY 2026 Plans:
- Continue to develop cost-effective human-AI communication to incorporate complex logical knowledge and reasoning into AI
systems, enabling much higher assurance in decision support than machine learning alone can, for obligations and permissions,
e.g., in course-of-action planning and autonomous systems.
- Begin creation of methods for AI to support peer-to-peer groups with doing argumentation reasoning, to increase asynchrony,
speed, size, and quality.

