Title: Compartmentalization and Privilege Management (CPM)                                                                                  -             -          15.045
Description: The Compartmentalization and Privilege Management (CPM) program is developing new system frameworks,
architectures, and tooling to provide fine-grained, least-privileged compartmentalization that enables prevention and containment
of cyber attacks. Today's information systems are structured around a monolithic core, the kernel, that operates within a single
protection domain at a single high privilege-level. A monolithic kernel contains many separate components without protection
boundaries between them. A single compromise anywhere in the system allows attackers effectively unlimited access through
an extended sequence of exploits, privilege escalation, and lateral motion. CPM is developing technologies and tools to
compartmentalize large, legacy software systems automatically and designing processor architectures and system software to
enforce a compartment and privilege-level regime. CPM tools and architectures will prevent initial penetrations from propagating
into successful cyber attacks.

Prior to FY 2026, this program was funded in PE 0601101E, Project ES-02.

FY 2026 Plans:
- Produce code compartmentalization and processor and policy enforcement implementations.
- Develop attack campaign test cases for Department of Defense-relevant applications with particular interest in attacks involving
extended sequences of exploits, privilege escalation, and lateral motion.
- Evaluate effectiveness and overhead of compartmentalization and privilege management systems using operating system
attack campaign test cases.
FY 2025 to FY 2026 Increase/Decrease Statement:
The FY 2026 increase reflects transfer of the program from PE 0601101E, Project ES-02 to this PE/Project.
Title: Disruptive Microtechnologies Sciences Studies and Concepts                                                                           -             -           1.652
Description: The Disruptive Microtechnologies Sciences Studies and Concepts will examine the fundamental science needed
to advance disruptive microtechnologies. This program will also examine ways to take advantage of commercial scaling while
building in superior capabilities for defense systems through design, integration, and hardware security. These studies may lead to
the development of new programs in these areas.

FY 2026 Plans:
- Examine current and burgeoning technologies for creation of disruptive microtechnologies.

